{"title_page": "Atmore, Alabama", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Alabama, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Atmore\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = atmoretrain10.jpg\n|image_caption            = Former Atmore Amtrak station\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = File:Escambia County Alabama Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Atmore Highlighted 0103004.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Atmore in Escambia County, Alabama.\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Alabama|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alabama]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Escambia County, Alabama|Escambia]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 56.82\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 21.94\n|area_land_km2            = 56.62\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 21.86\n|area_water_km2           = 0.19\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.07\n|elevation_ft             = 282\n|elevation_m              = 86\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 10194\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 165.20\n|population_density_sq_mi = 427.87\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|31|1|23|N|87|29|31|W|region:US-AL|display=inline}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 36502-36504\n|area_code                = [[Area code 251|251]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 01-03004\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0113272\n|website                  = {{URL|https://cityofatmore.com/}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 9354\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_01.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Atmore''' is a city in [[Escambia County, Alabama|Escambia County]], [[Alabama]], [[United States]]. It incorporated in 1907.<ref>http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/article/h-3111</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 10,194,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0103004| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Atmore city, Alabama| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American Factfinder| accessdate=January 21, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213083957/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0103004| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> with an estimated population of 9,354 in 2018.<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/> Atmore is in the planning stages to increase its economic base with additions in its new Rivercane development along the [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|I-65 corridor]].\n\nAtmore has completed requirements to be recognized as an Alabama Community of Excellence at the upcoming Alabama League of Municipalities Convention. City officials are also working with the [[Alabama Historical Commission]] to have the downtown district listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\">{{cite web|title=City of Atmore.com|url=http://cityofatmore.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2007, Atmore celebrated its centenary.\n\nThe federally recognized [[Poarch Band of Creek Indians]] is headquartered in Atmore.\n\n==History==\nAtmore was first recorded as a stop (Williams Station)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.goldbug.com/|title = SiteFind, v. 3.0, CD and free online versions available|orig-year = copyright 1996-2008|accessdate = |website = The Gold Bug|publisher = The Gold Bug|last = Ettinger|first = Adrian B.}}</ref> on the [[Mobile and Great Northern Railroad]]. The town was named after C.P. Atmore, General Passenger Agent of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], who was a friend of Mr. Carney, who owned a sawmill in town and was a prominent citizen. The town was originally going to be named \"Carney\", but Mr. Carney had a brother who had already established a town and named it Carney nearby. The town then decided to let Mr. Carney name the town. He named it after his close friend Mr. Atmore, who never visited Atmore.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1900/05/30/archives/cp-atmore-drops-dead-was-general-passenger-agent-of-the-louisville.html C.P. ATMORE DROPS DEAD] ''C.P. ATMORE'' (retrieved 16 August 2010)</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAtmore is located in western Escambia County at {{Coord|31|1|23|N|87|29|31|W|type:city}} (31.023183, -87.492067).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Its southern border is the [[Florida]] state line. The center of town is at the intersection of [[U.S. Route 31]] and [[Alabama State Route 21]], while a new section of the city has been incorporated {{convert|6|mi|0}} to the north around Exit 57 of [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]]. US 31 leads southwest {{convert|20|mi}} to [[Bay Minette, Alabama|Bay Minette]] and east {{convert|28|mi}} to [[Brewton, Alabama|Brewton]]. [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] is {{convert|51|mi}} to the southwest via US 31 and I-65, while [[Pensacola, Florida]], is {{convert|49|mi}} south via AL 21, [[Florida State Road 97]], and [[U.S. Route 29 in Florida|U.S. Route 29]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], Atmore has a total area of {{convert|56.8|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|56.6|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.2|km2|order=flip}}, or 0.34%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1910= 1060\n|1920= 1775\n|1930= 3035\n|1940= 3200\n|1950= 5720\n|1960= 8173\n|1970= 8293\n|1980= 8789\n|1990= 8046\n|2000= 7676\n|2010= 10194\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=9354\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAtmore first appeared on the 1910 U.S. Census as an incorporated town.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41033935v1-8ch1.pdf, 1910 AL Census</ref> By 1930, it became the largest city in Escambia County, though lost the title to former holder [[Brewton, Alabama|Brewton]] in 1940. It became the largest city again in 1950 and has held the distinction to date (2010). In 2010, the city became majority Black for the first time.<ref>http://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-1-2.pdf, 2010 AL Census</ref>\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, the [[population density]] was 1228 people per square mile (469.8/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,480 housing units at an average density of 419.3 per square mile (160.4/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 55.4% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 39.3% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 1.8% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.3% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.1% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. 1.8% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.<ref name=\"Data.com\">{{cite web|title=Data.com|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Atmore-Alabama.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Racial Makeup\">{{cite web|title=Racial Makeup|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0103004|access-date=2017-08-30|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213114325/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0103004|archive-date=2020-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were 3,002 households out of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 34.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 23.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.1% were non-families. 33.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 3.09.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 18.6% under the age of 18, 9.1% from 18 to 24, 34.5% from 25 to 44, 24.9% from 45 to 64, and 12.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37.4 years. For every 100 females, there were 155.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 207.4 males.\n\n===2000 Census data===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, the [[population density]] was 922.5 people per square mile (356.2/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,535 housing units at an average density of 424.9 per square mile (164.0/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 49.48% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 46.31% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 2.41% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.47% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.05% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.91% from two or more races. 0.73% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\nThere were 3,148 households out of which 29.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 20.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.2% were non-families. 30.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.01.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 26.4% under the age of 18, 9.0% from 18 to 24, 24.9% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 17.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 79.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 74.7 males.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\n==Atmore Census Division (1960-)==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1960= 12373\n|1970= 12221\n|1980= 13672\n|1990= 12645\n|2000= 12980\n|2010= 12372\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAtmore was created a census division in 1960 following the general reorganization of county precincts.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/37721510v1p2ch2.pdf, 1960 AL Census</ref> Prior to 1960, Atmore was within the former Escambia County 7th precinct of Canoe.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/23761117v1ch04.pdf, 1950 AL Census</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAtmore is home to various local schools within the Escambia County Public School System, including:   Rachel Patterson Elementary School, Escambia County Middle School (the largest school in the system), and Escambia County High School (the first public county high school in the state of Alabama). It is also home to [[Escambia Academy]] and Atmore Christian School, as well as several other private schools and colleges including reid state.\n\nAtmore is home to an adjunct campus of [[Coastal Alabama Community College Brewton]] based in Brewton, which offers associate degrees and technical school training.\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nAtmore is governed by a mayor and members of a city council elected from five districts within the city.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\nThe [[Holman Correctional Facility]], a prison of the [[Alabama Department of Corrections]] (ADOC), is within the city limits {{convert|9|mi|km}} north of the center of Atmore.<ref>\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=12 Holman Correctional Facility] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808194322/http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=12 |date=2010-08-08 }}.\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on August 15, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"HolmanCRProfile\">\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/docs/AnnualRpts/2003AnnualReport.pdf Annual Report Fiscal Year 2003].\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. 33/84. Retrieved on August 15, 2010.</ref> Holman has a male [[death row]]<!--Alabama has two male death rows!!!--> and the State of Alabama [[execution chamber]].<ref name=\"HolmanCRProfile\"/> In addition [[Fountain Correctional Facility]] is {{convert|10|mi|0}} north of Atmore, in a formerly unincorporated area that is now within the city limits.<ref name=\"f\">\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=9 Fountain / JO Davis Correctional Facility] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616081250/http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=9 |date=2011-06-16 }}.\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on July 4, 2011.</ref>\n\nAtmore is close by Interstate 65. US Highway 31 and State Highway 21 pass through the center of the city. It is also home for major coast-to-coast freight haulers, including the [[Alabama and Gulf Coast Railway]] and [[CSX]]. In addition, Atmore has a municipal airport.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\n==Local economy==\nFor most of the 20th century, the Atmore area was primarily a farming, timber, and light industry community. Major commercial industries have been Masland Carpets, Alto, and a local lumber company. For many years, the [[VF Corporation|Vanity Fair]] lingerie company operated a manufacturing sewing plant in Atmore, offering employment to local citizens and surrounding communities.\n\nWith federal recognition and the founding of gaming casinos, the [[Poarch Band of Creek Indians]] near Exit 54 on [[I-65]], {{convert|6|mi|0}} northwest of the center of Atmore, has increased its relative economic contributions to the region. The tribe operates the Wind Creek Casino and Hotel, which provides for tourism and conferences, adjacent to I-65 Exit 57.<ref>[http://www.500nations.com/Alabama_Casinos.asp Alabama Casinos.] ''500 Nations.'' (retrieved 23 February 2009)</ref>  Wind Creek is one of just a few four-diamond hotels in the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wind Creek Casino|url=http://www.windcreekcasino.com}}</ref>\n\n==Health care and recreation==\nAtmore Community Hospital, an affiliate of Infirmary Health Systems of Mobile, offers full acute care in a two-story facility.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\nAtmore has several recreational and sports facilities, including Atmore Heritage Park and Claude D. Kelley State Park.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Atmore.com|url=http://www.cityofatmore.com}}</ref>\n\n==Local events==\n\n'''Mayfest''' \u2014 On the first Saturday in May at Tom Byrne Park, Atmore celebrates Mayfest with sports events, arts and crafts and a variety of food. There are many different forms of entertainment, including a Beautiful Baby Contest and a Pooch Parade.<ref name=\"Alabama Tourism Department\">{{cite web|title=Cities and Towns |url=http://www.alabama.travel/cities-towns/gulf/atmore |publisher=Sweet Home Alabama |accessdate=11 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528214318/http://www.alabama.travel/cities-towns/gulf/atmore |archivedate=28 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n'''Old-Time Fiddlers' Convention''' \u2014 Musicians from across the state come to Atmore the third Saturday in July to compete for prizes in the [[fiddle]], guitar, banjo, mandolin, and bands and vocals division.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweet Home Alabama|url=http://www.alabama.travel/events/atmore_rotary_clubs_old_time_fiddlers_convention_3#|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''A Taste of the South''' \u2014 Held annually at Heritage Park in September, A Taste of the South is an evening of entertainment and local food from the area's best cooks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Festival and Event Calendar|url=http://www.alabama.travel/upcoming-events/search?q=Atmore|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''Williams Station Day''' \u2014 Held the fourth Saturday of October, Williams Station Day celebrates Atmore's history beginning in 1866 as Williams Station. The event includes an arts and crafts show, an old time fiddlers' tent, professional entertainment, a model train show, and sugar cane mill.<ref>{{cite web| title=Williams Station Day, 21st Annual| url=http://www.alabama.travel/events/williams_station_day_21st_annual_-_web_submission| publisher=Alabama Department Tourism| accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Poarch Creek Indian Pow-wow''' \u2014 The local Poarch Creek Indians host an authentic Thanksgiving annually. Visitors enjoy turkey, dressing, and roasted corn as dancers from many tribes gather to compete. Over 100 booths display arts and crafts, quilts and other keepsakes of the Creek Indian culture.<ref>{{cite web| title=al.com| url=http://blog.al.com/living-press-register/2011/11/religion_is_integral_to_lives.html| accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Paul Birch (actor)|Paul Birch]], actor and the original \"Marlboro Man\",<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0083280/bio]</ref> born in Atmore\n* [[Bobby Brantley]], [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida|13th lieutenant governor of Florida]]\n* [[Glenn L. Emmons]], commissioner of the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]] from 1953 to 1961, native of Atmore<ref name=\"NYT 19530811\">''[[The New York Times]]''. \"Indian Director Sworn In: Glenn L. Emmons Takes Office Succeeding Dillon S. Myer.\" August 11, 1953.</ref>\n* [[Evander Holyfield]], four-time world heavyweight boxing champion, born in Atmore\n* [[William C. Maxwell]], namesake of [[Maxwell Air Force Base]]\n* [[Don McNeal]], star defensive back for Alabama and the Miami Dolphins, born and raised in Atmore\n* [[Ron Middleton (American football)|Ron Middleton]], former [[Auburn University]] and NFL [[tight end]]\n* [[Michael Williams (running back)|Michael Williams]], NFL player\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Climate==\nClimate is characterized by mild to high temperatures and evenly distributed precipitation throughout the year.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] sub-type for this climate is \"[[Humid subtropical climate|Cfa]]\" (Humid Subtropical Climate).<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=204010&cityname=Atmore%2C+Alabama%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Atmore, Alabama]</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Atmore, Alabama\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 61\n|Feb high F = 65\n|Mar high F = 71\n|Apr high F = 78\n|May high F = 86\n|Jun high F = 90\n|Jul high F = 91\n|Aug high F = 91\