ia County, Alabama}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cities in Escambia County, Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|City in Alabama, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Atmore\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|image_skyline            = atmoretrain10.jpg\n|image_caption            = Former Atmore Amtrak station\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = File:Escambia County Alabama Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Atmore Highlighted 0103004.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Atmore in Escambia County, Alabama.\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Alabama|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Alabama]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Escambia County, Alabama|Escambia]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 56.82\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 21.94\n|area_land_km2            = 56.62\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 21.86\n|area_water_km2           = 0.19\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.07\n|elevation_ft             = 282\n|elevation_m              = 86\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 10194\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 165.20\n|population_density_sq_mi = 427.87\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|31|1|23|N|87|29|31|W|region:US-AL|display=inline}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 36502-36504\n|area_code                = [[Area code 251|251]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 01-03004\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0113272\n|website                  = {{URL|https://cityofatmore.com/}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 9354\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_01.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Atmore''' is a city in [[Escambia County, Alabama|Escambia County]], [[Alabama]], [[United States]]. It incorporated in 1907.<ref>http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/article/h-3111</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 10,194,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0103004| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Atmore city, Alabama| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau| work=American Factfinder| accessdate=January 21, 2016| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213083957/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US0103004| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> with an estimated population of 9,354 in 2018.<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/> Atmore is in the planning stages to increase its economic base with additions in its new Rivercane development along the [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|I-65 corridor]].\n\nAtmore has completed requirements to be recognized as an Alabama Community of Excellence at the upcoming Alabama League of Municipalities Convention. City officials are also working with the [[Alabama Historical Commission]] to have the downtown district listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\">{{cite web|title=City of Atmore.com|url=http://cityofatmore.com/}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2007, Atmore celebrated its centenary.\n\nThe federally recognized [[Poarch Band of Creek Indians]] is headquartered in Atmore.\n\n==History==\nAtmore was first recorded as a stop (Williams Station)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.goldbug.com/|title = SiteFind, v. 3.0, CD and free online versions available|orig-year = copyright 1996-2008|accessdate = |website = The Gold Bug|publisher = The Gold Bug|last = Ettinger|first = Adrian B.}}</ref> on the [[Mobile and Great Northern Railroad]]. The town was named after C.P. Atmore, General Passenger Agent of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]], who was a friend of Mr. Carney, who owned a sawmill in town and was a prominent citizen. The town was originally going to be named \"Carney\", but Mr. Carney had a brother who had already established a town and named it Carney nearby. The town then decided to let Mr. Carney name the town. He named it after his close friend Mr. Atmore, who never visited Atmore.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1900/05/30/archives/cp-atmore-drops-dead-was-general-passenger-agent-of-the-louisville.html C.P. ATMORE DROPS DEAD] ''C.P. ATMORE'' (retrieved 16 August 2010)</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAtmore is located in western Escambia County at {{Coord|31|1|23|N|87|29|31|W|type:city}} (31.023183, -87.492067).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Its southern border is the [[Florida]] state line. The center of town is at the intersection of [[U.S. Route 31]] and [[Alabama State Route 21]], while a new section of the city has been incorporated {{convert|6|mi|0}} to the north around Exit 57 of [[Interstate 65 in Alabama|Interstate 65]]. US 31 leads southwest {{convert|20|mi}} to [[Bay Minette, Alabama|Bay Minette]] and east {{convert|28|mi}} to [[Brewton, Alabama|Brewton]]. [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] is {{convert|51|mi}} to the southwest via US 31 and I-65, while [[Pensacola, Florida]], is {{convert|49|mi}} south via AL 21, [[Florida State Road 97]], and [[U.S. Route 29 in Florida|U.S. Route 29]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], Atmore has a total area of {{convert|56.8|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|56.6|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.2|km2|order=flip}}, or 0.34%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1910= 1060\n|1920= 1775\n|1930= 3035\n|1940= 3200\n|1950= 5720\n|1960= 8173\n|1970= 8293\n|1980= 8789\n|1990= 8046\n|2000= 7676\n|2010= 10194\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=9354\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAtmore first appeared on the 1910 U.S. Census as an incorporated town.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/41033935v1-8ch1.pdf, 1910 AL Census</ref> By 1930, it became the largest city in Escambia County, though lost the title to former holder [[Brewton, Alabama|Brewton]] in 1940. It became the largest city again in 1950 and has held the distinction to date (2010). In 2010, the city became majority Black for the first time.<ref>http://www.census.gov/prod/cen2010/cph-1-2.pdf, 2010 AL Census</ref>\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, the [[population density]] was 1228 people per square mile (469.8/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,480 housing units at an average density of 419.3 per square mile (160.4/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 55.4% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 39.3% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 1.8% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.3% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.1% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. 1.8% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.<ref name=\"Data.com\">{{cite web|title=Data.com|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Atmore-Alabama.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Racial Makeup\">{{cite web|title=Racial Makeup|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0103004|access-date=2017-08-30|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213114325/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/1600000US0103004|archive-date=2020-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThere were 3,002 households out of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 34.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 23.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 37.1% were non-families. 33.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.43 and the average family size was 3.09.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 18.6% under the age of 18, 9.1% from 18 to 24, 34.5% from 25 to 44, 24.9% from 45 to 64, and 12.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37.4 years. For every 100 females, there were 155.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 207.4 males.\n\n===2000 Census data===\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000, the [[population density]] was 922.5 people per square mile (356.2/km<sup>2</sup>). There were 3,535 housing units at an average density of 424.9 per square mile (164.0/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the city was 49.48% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 46.31% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 2.41% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.47% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.05% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.91% from two or more races. 0.73% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\nThere were 3,148 households out of which 29.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 20.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.2% were non-families. 30.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.40 and the average family size was 3.01.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 26.4% under the age of 18, 9.0% from 18 to 24, 24.9% from 25 to 44, 22.6% from 45 to 64, and 17.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 79.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 74.7 males.<ref name=\"Data.com\"/>\n\n==Atmore Census Division (1960-)==\n{{US Census population|align=left\n|1960= 12373\n|1970= 12221\n|1980= 13672\n|1990= 12645\n|2000= 12980\n|2010= 12372\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 6, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAtmore was created a census division in 1960 following the general reorganization of county precincts.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/37721510v1p2ch2.pdf, 1960 AL Census</ref> Prior to 1960, Atmore was within the former Escambia County 7th precinct of Canoe.<ref>http://www2.census.gov/prod2/decennial/documents/23761117v1ch04.pdf, 1950 AL Census</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAtmore is home to various local schools within the Escambia County Public School System, including:   Rachel Patterson Elementary School,, Escambia County Middle School (the largest school in the system), and Escambia County High School (the first public county high school in the state of Alabama). It is also home to [[Escambia Academy]] and Atmore Christian School, as well as several other private schools and colleges including reid state.\n\nAtmore is home to an adjunct campus of [[Coastal Alabama Community College Brewton]] based in Brewton, which offers associate degrees and technical school training.\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nAtmore is governed by a mayor and members of a city council elected from five districts within the city.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\nThe [[Holman Correctional Facility]], a prison of the [[Alabama Department of Corrections]] (ADOC), is within the city limits {{convert|9|mi|km}} north of the center of Atmore.<ref>\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=12 Holman Correctional Facility] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808194322/http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=12 |date=2010-08-08 }}.\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on August 15, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"HolmanCRProfile\">\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/docs/AnnualRpts/2003AnnualReport.pdf Annual Report Fiscal Year 2003].\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. 33/84. Retrieved on August 15, 2010.</ref> Holman has a male [[death row]]<!--Alabama has two male death rows!!!--> and the State of Alabama [[execution chamber]].<ref name=\"HolmanCRProfile\"/> In addition [[Fountain Correctional Facility]] is {{convert|10|mi|0}} north of Atmore, in a formerly unincorporated area that is now within the city limits.<ref name=\"f\">\"[http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=9 Fountain / JO Davis Correctional Facility] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616081250/http://www.doc.state.al.us/facility.asp?id=9 |date=2011-06-16 }}.\" [[Alabama Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on July 4, 2011.</ref>\n\nAtmore is close by Interstate 65. US Highway 31 and State Highway 21 pass through the center of the city. It is also home for major coast-to-coast freight haulers, including the [[Alabama and Gulf Coast Railway]] and [[CSX]]. In addition, Atmore has a municipal airport.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\n==Local economy==\nFor most of the 20th century, the Atmore area was primarily a farming, timber, and light industry community. Major commercial industries have been Masland Carpets, Alto, and a local lumber company. For many years, the [[VF Corporation|Vanity Fair]] lingerie company operated a manufacturing sewing plant in Atmore, offering employment to local citizens and surrounding communities.\n\nWith federal recognition and the founding of gaming casinos, the [[Poarch Band of Creek Indians]] near Exit 54 on [[I-65]], {{convert|6|mi|0}} northwest of the center of Atmore, has increased its relative economic contributions to the region. The tribe operates the Wind Creek Casino and Hotel, which provides for tourism and conferences, adjacent to I-65 Exit 57.<ref>[http://www.500nations.com/Alabama_Casinos.asp Alabama Casinos.] ''500 Nations.'' (retrieved 23 February 2009)</ref>  Wind Creek is one of just a few four-diamond hotels in the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wind Creek Casino|url=http://www.windcreekcasino.com}}</ref>\n\n==Health care and recreation==\nAtmore Community Hospital, an affiliate of Infirmary Health Systems of Mobile, offers full acute care in a two-story facility.<ref name=\"City of Atmore.com\"/>\n\nAtmore has several recreational and sports facilities, including Atmore Heritage Park and Claude D. Kelley State Park.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Atmore.com|url=http://www.cityofatmore.com}}</ref>\n\n==Local events==\n\n'''Mayfest''' \u2014 On the first Saturday in May at Tom Byrne Park, Atmore celebrates Mayfest with sports events, arts and crafts and a variety of food. There are many different forms of entertainment, including a Beautiful Baby Contest and a Pooch Parade.<ref name=\"Alabama Tourism Department\">{{cite web|title=Cities and Towns |url=http://www.alabama.travel/cities-towns/gulf/atmore |publisher=Sweet Home Alabama |accessdate=11 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528214318/http://www.alabama.travel/cities-towns/gulf/atmore |archivedate=28 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n'''Old-Time Fiddlers' Convention''' \u2014 Musicians from across the state come to Atmore the third Saturday in July to compete for prizes in the [[fiddle]], guitar, banjo, mandolin, and bands and vocals division.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sweet Home Alabama|url=http://www.alabama.travel/events/atmore_rotary_clubs_old_time_fiddlers_convention_3#|accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''A Taste of the South''' \u2014 Held annually at Heritage Park in September, A Taste of the South is an evening of entertainment and local food from the area's best cooks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Festival and Event Calendar|url=http://www.alabama.travel/upcoming-events/search?q=Atmore|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''Williams Station Day''' \u2014 Held the fourth Saturday of October, Williams Station Day celebrates Atmore's history beginning in 1866 as Williams Station. The event includes an arts and crafts show, an old time fiddlers' tent, professional entertainment, a model train show, and sugar cane mill.<ref>{{cite web| title=Williams Station Day, 21st Annual| url=http://www.alabama.travel/events/williams_station_day_21st_annual_-_web_submission| publisher=Alabama Department Tourism| accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Poarch Creek Indian Pow-wow''' \u2014 The local Poarch Creek Indians host an authentic Thanksgiving annually. Visitors enjoy turkey, dressing, and roasted corn as dancers from many tribes gather to compete. Over 100 booths display arts and crafts, quilts and other keepsakes of the Creek Indian culture.<ref>{{cite web| title=al.com| url=http://blog.al.com/living-press-register/2011/11/religion_is_integral_to_lives.html| accessdate=11 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Paul Birch (actor)|Paul Birch]], actor and the original \"Marlboro Man\",<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0083280/bio]</ref> born in Atmore\n* [[Bobby Brantley]], [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida|13th lieutenant governor of Florida]]\n* [[Glenn L. Emmons]], commissioner of the [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]] from 1953 to 1961, native of Atmore<ref name=\"NYT 19530811\">''[[The New York Times]]''. \"Indian Director Sworn In: Glenn L. Emmons Takes Office Succeeding Dillon S. Myer.\" August 11, 1953.</ref>\n* [[Evander Holyfield]], four-time world heavyweight boxing champion, born in Atmore\n* [[William C. Maxwell]], namesake of [[Maxwell Air Force Base]]\n* [[Don McNeal]], star defensive back for Alabama and the Miami Dolphins, born and raised in Atmore\n* [[Ron Middleton (American football)|Ron Middleton]], former [[Auburn University]] and NFL [[tight end]]\n* [[Michael Williams (running back)|Michael Williams]], NFL player\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Climate==\nClimate is characterized by mild to high temperatures and evenly distributed precipitation throughout the year.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] sub-type for this climate is \"[[Humid subtropical climate|Cfa]]\" (Humid Subtropical Climate).<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=204010&cityname=Atmore%2C+Alabama%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Atmore, Alabama]</ref>\n{{Weather box\n|location = Atmore, Alabama\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan high F = 61\n|Feb high F = 65\n|Mar high F = 71\n|Apr high F = 78\n|May high F = 86\n|Jun high F = 90\n|Jul high F = 91\n|Aug high F = 91\n|Sep high F = 87\n|Oct high F = 80\n|Nov high F = 70\n|Dec high F = 62\n|year high F = 78\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 42\n|Mar low F = 47\n|Apr low F = 54\n|May low F = 62\n|Jun low F = 69\n|Jul low F = 71\n|Aug low F = 70\n|Sep low F = 66\n|Oct low F = 55\n|Nov low F = 46\n|Dec low F = 40\n|year low F = 55\n|Jan precipitation inch = 5.5\n|Feb precipitation inch = 5\n|Mar precipitation inch = 6.7\n|Apr precipitation inch = 5.2\n|May precipitation inch = 4.8\n|Jun precipitation inch = 5.8\n|Jul precipitation inch = 7.3\n|Aug precipitation inch = 5.7\n|Sep precipitation inch = 5\n|Oct precipitation inch = 2.9\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.7\n|Dec precipitation inch = 4.8\n|year precipitation inch = 63.4\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>\n{{cite web\n|url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=204010&cityname=Atmore-Alabama\n|publisher=Weatherbase\n|title=Weatherbase.com\n|year=2013\n}}\nRetrieved on August 4, 2013.\n</ref>\n|date=August 2013\n}}\n\n==Photo Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Main Street Atmore Oct 2014 2.jpg|Main Street Atmore\nFile:Main Street Atmore Oct 2014 1.jpg|Main Street Atmore\nFile:Atmore Alabama Post Office.jpg|Atmore Post Office\nFile:Atmore Municipal Airport.jpg|Atmore Municipal Airport\nFile:Library picture.jpg|Atmore Library\nFile:Owen-Lufkin House Oct 2014 1.jpg|Owen-Lufkin House\nFile:Evander Holyfield 2010 Indy 500 Pole Day.JPG|Evander Holyfield, Native Son of Atmore\nFile:US31 North - AL21 Atmore (41409917190).jpg|Roadsigns in Atmore\nFile:Wind Creek Casino sign in Atmore, Alabama LCCN2010640198.tif|Wind Creek Casino sign, Atmore\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Atmore, Alabama}}\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [http://www.cityofatmore.com City of Atmore official website]\n* [http://www.atmorechamber.com Atmore Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* [http://www.poarchcreekindians.org The Poarch Band of Creek Indians]\n{{Coord|display=title|31.023183|-87.492067}}\n{{Escambia County, Alabama}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Cities in Escambia County, Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: ,,  \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmore,_Alabama"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Joseph (politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n| name               = Bernard Joseph\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            =\n| office             = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start         = 21 May 2015\n| term_end           = 7 May 2019\n| constituency       = \n| office2            = [[National Assembly (South Africa) |Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start2        = 21 May 2014\n| term_end2          = 20 May 2015\n| constituency2      = [[Western Cape]]\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = South African \n| party              = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n| otherparty         = [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| known_for          = Being the Chairperson of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] in the [[Western Cape]].\n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Bernard Daniel Joseph''' is a South African politician. A member of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]],  he served as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 2015 to 2019. He was the first chairperson of the party in the Western Cape. From 2014 to 2015, he was a Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]]. Before he held elected office, he was an employee at the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Community Safety Department]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190412124457/http://www.wcpp.gov.za/node/2017 Hon Bernard Joseph], Western Cape Provincial Parliament website (wcpp). Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n==Political career==\nHe was a member of the Congress of the People before he joined the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]. Joseph said that he left the party because he felt that the party lacked leadership and movement. He joined the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] to implement the party's policies.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-names-w-cape-candidates-1665839 EFF names W Cape candidates]. IOL. Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n\nBefore the [[2014 South African general election]], the Economic Freedom Fighters announced their election lists. Joseph was the first candidate on the party's regional list, third on the party's provincial list and seventy-second on the national list. He was elected to the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] and took office as a Member on 21 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.pa.org.za/person/bernard-daniel-joseph/#experience Mr Bernard Daniel Joseph]. People's Assembly. Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n\nHe resigned as a Member of the National Assembly in May 2015. He was subsequently sworn in as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] on 21 May 2015. He left the Provincial Parliament in May 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joseph, Bernard}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable]]\n| name               = Bernard Joseph\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            =\n| office             = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start         = 21 May 2015\n| term_end           = 7 May 2019\n| constituency       = \n| office2            = [[National Assembly (South Africa) |Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start2        = 21 May 2014\n| term_end2          = 20 May 2015\n| constituency2      = [[Western Cape]]\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = South African \n| party              = [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]\n| otherparty         = [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| known_for          = Being the Chairperson of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] in the [[Western Cape]].\n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Bernard Daniel Joseph''' is a South African politician. A member of the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]],  he served as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 2015 to 2019. He was the first chairperson of the party in the Western Cape. From 2014 to 2015, he was a Member of the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]]. Before he held elected office, he was an employee at the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Community Safety Department]].<ref>[http://www.wcpp.gov.za/node/2017 Hon Bernard Joseph], Western Cape Provincial Parliament website (wcpp). Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n==Political career==\nHe was a member of the Congress of the People before he joined the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]]. Joseph said that he left the party because he felt that the party lacked leadership and movement. He joined the [[Economic Freedom Fighters]] to implement the party's policies.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eff-names-w-cape-candidates-1665839 EFF names W Cape candidates]. IOL. Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n\nBefore the [[2014 South African general election]], the Economic Freedom Fighters announced their election lists. Joseph was the first candidate on the party's regional list, third on the party's provincial list and seventy-second on the national list. He was elected to the [[National Assembly (South Africa)|National Assembly]] and took office as a Member on 21 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.pa.org.za/person/bernard-daniel-joseph/#experience Mr Bernard Daniel Joseph]. People's Assembly. Retrieved on 2 January 2019.</ref>\n\nHe resigned as a Member of the National Assembly in May 2015. He was subsequently sworn in as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] on 21 May 2015. He left the Provincial Parliament in May 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Economic Freedom Fighters}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joseph, Bernard}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Economic Freedom Fighters politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed. Archived", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Joseph_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "USNS Mercy (T-AH-19)", "text_new": "{{Other ships|USS Mercy}}\n{{short description|Hospital ship of the United States Navy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=yes}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:USNS Mercy leaving San Diego Bay.jpg|300px|USNS Mercy]]\n|Ship caption=USNS ''Mercy'' leaving San Diego Bay, May 2008\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=[[Mercy]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]]\n|Ship laid down= 12 June 1974 (As {{sclass-|San Clemente|oil tanker}} SS ''Worth'' MA-299)\n|Ship launched= 1 July 1975 (in [[San Diego, California]])\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=8 November 1986 (to US Navy)\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport= [[San Diego, California]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|7390454}}\n* {{MMSI Number|367816000}}\n* [[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: NMER\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Active\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mercy|hospital ship}}\n|Ship capacity = 1000 patient beds\n|Ship displacement=65,552 tons<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship length={{cvt|894|ft}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship beam={{cvt|106|ft}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship propulsion=two boilers, two GE turbines, one shaft, {{cvt|24,500|hp|MW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{cvt|17|kn}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=*12 civilian and 58 military during [[Reduced Operating Status]]\n* 61 civilian and 1,214 military during Full Operating Status\n|Ship time to activate=5 days\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:USNS Mercy T-AH-19 2005.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' being refuelled at sea by {{USNS|Tippecanoe|T-AO 199|6}}, April 2005 during the ship's mission to aid victims of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]].]]\n[[File:USNS Mercy off Jolo.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' anchored off [[Jolo]], Philippines in June 2006.]]\n[[File:USNS Mercy off Dili.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' anchored in [[Dili]], East Timor, as part of \"Pacific Partnership 2008.\"]]\n[[File:US Navy 060704-N-1577S-002 Medical staff from Operation Smile and the Military Treatment Facility (MTF) aboard the Military Sealift Command (MSC) hospital ship USNS Mercy (T-AH 19), perform a cleft lip surgery.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Medical staff from [[Operation Smile]] and the [[Military Treatment Facility]] (MTF) aboard ''Mercy'', perform a [[cleft lip]] surgery during the ship's visit to provide humanitarian and civic assistance to the people of [[Bangladesh]].]]\n\n'''USNS ''Mercy'' (T-AH-19)''' is the [[lead ship]] of [[Mercy class hospital ship|her class]] of [[hospital ship]]s in non-commissioned service with the [[United States Navy]]. Her sister ship is {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20}}. She is the third US Navy ship to be named for the virtue [[mercy]]. In accordance with the [[Geneva Conventions]], ''Mercy'' and her crew do not carry any offensive weapons, though defensive weapons are available. Attacking ''Mercy'' is a [[war crime]].<ref>Diplomatic Conference of Geneva of 1949 {{cite web|url= http://www.icrc.org/ihl.nsf/COM/370-580040?OpenDocument|title=Chapter III: Hospital ships, Article 35 \u2013 Conditions not Depriving Hospital Ships of Protection|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Mercy'' was built as a {{sclass-|San Clemente|oil tanker}}, '''SS ''Worth''''', by [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]], San Diego, California, in 1976. Starting in July 1984, she was renamed and converted to a hospital ship by the same company. [[Ship naming and launching|Launched]] on 20 July 1985, ''Mercy'' was placed in service on 8 November 1986. She has a raised forecastle, a transom stern, a bulbous bow, an extended deckhouse with a forward bridge, and a helicopter-landing deck with a flight-control facility.\n\nThe conversions from oil tankers cost $208 million per ship and took 35 months to complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/tah-19-history.htm|title=T-AH 19 Mercy Class \u2013 Program History|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Mercy''-class hospital ships are the third largest ships in the US Navy Fleet by length, surpassed only by the nuclear-powered {{sclass-|Nimitz|aircraft carrier|5}}- and {{sclass-|Gerald R. Ford|aircraft carrier|0}} [[supercarrier]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |title=Patient Care |website=Command Facilities |publisher=USNS Mercy |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323010700/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/Commandinfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |archivedate=23 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nHer primary mission is to provide rapid, flexible, and mobile acute medical and surgical services to support Marine Corps Air/Ground Task Forces deployed ashore, Army and Air Force units deployed ashore, and naval amphibious task forces and battle forces afloat. Secondarily, she provides mobile surgical hospital service for use by appropriate US Government agencies in disaster and humanitarian relief, and limited humanitarian care incident to these missions and to peacetime military operations.<ref name=\"med.navy.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |title=Command Mission |website=USNS Mercy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813132035/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |archivedate=2009-08-13|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Mercy'', homeported in San Diego, is normally in reduced operating status. Her crew remains a part of the staff of [[Naval Medical Center San Diego]] until ordered to sea, at which time they have five days to fully activate the ship to a NATO Role III Medical Treatment Facility, the highest only to{{clarify|date=March 2020}} shore based fixed facilities outside the theater of operations.<ref name=\"med.navy.mil\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/logi-en/1997/lo-1610.htm |title=NATO Logistics Handbook: Chapter 16: Medical Support |work=nato.int |date=October 1997 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> Like most USNS ships, mariners from the US Navy's [[Military Sealift Command]] are responsible for navigation, propulsion, and most deck duties on board.<ref name=inv>{{cite web |url=https://www.militaryfactory.com/ships/detail.asp?ship_id=usns-mercy-t-ah-19-hospital-ship-usn |title=USNS Mercy (T-AH 19) Hospital Ship |work=Military Factory  |publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> ''Mercy'' is as of 2012 part of MSC's Service Support Program. However, the \"Medical Treatment Facility\", or hospital on the ship, is commanded by a captain of the [[Medical Corps (United States Navy)|Navy Medical Corps]] or [[Navy Nurse Corps]].\n\nSince March 27, 2020, ''Mercy'' has been stationed in Los Angeles, California, to help combat the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-pandemic.html|title=Navy's 1,000-bed hospital ship arrives in Los Angeles to ease surge of coronavirus patients \u2013 here's what's inside|last=Macias|first=Amanda|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Deployments==\n\n===Philippine Training Mission (1987)===\nOn 27 February 1987, ''Mercy'' began training while en route on a humanitarian cruise to the Philippines and the South Pacific. The staff included [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]], [[Indian Navy]], [[United States Army|U.S. Army]], and [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] active duty and reserve personnel; [[United States Public Health Service]]; medical providers from the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]]; and [[Military Sealift Command|MSC]] civilian mariners. Over 62,000 outpatients and almost 1,000 inpatients were treated at seven Philippine and South Pacific ports. ''Mercy'' returned to [[Oakland, California]], on 13 July 1987.\n\n===Operation Desert Shield/Desert Storm (1990\u201391)===\nOn 9 August 1990, ''Mercy'' was activated in support of [[Gulf War#Operation Desert Shield|Operation Desert Shield]]. Departing on 15 August, she arrived in the [[Persian Gulf]] on 15 September. For the next six months, ''Mercy'' provided support to multinational allied forces. She admitted 690 patients and performed almost 300 surgeries. After treating the 21 American and two Italian repatriated [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]], she departed for home on 16 March 1991, arriving in Oakland on 23 April.\n\n===Operation Unified Assistance (2004)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego on 5 January 2005 en route to the [[2004 Indian Ocean tsunami|tsunami]]-devastated regions of [[South East Asia]], where she provided medical care to the victims of the disaster as part of [[Operation Unified Assistance]], and further care as part of Theater Security Cooperation Program 2005. Combined, she provided 108,000 patient services, rendered by members of the Department of Defense, Project Hope, and the [[U.S. Public Health Service|United States Public Health Service]].\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2006)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego in 2006 as the inaugural deployment of [[Pacific Partnership]], an ongoing Civic Assistance mission designed to \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". She visited several ports in the South Pacific Ocean including [[the Philippines]], Indonesia, and [[Banda Aceh]]. The ship's primary mission was to provide humanitarian assistance to these countries, and its staff included several non-governmental organizations, doctors from the armed services of several countries, as well as active-duty and reserve military providers from many branches of the US armed forces.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2008)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego on 14 April 2008 for \"Pacific Partnership 2008\", a four-month humanitarian and civic [[Military deployment|deployment]] in Southeast Asia and Oceania. ''Mercy'', with its 900 officers and sailors, included 300 US health and construction experts. Partners participating in the mission included the nations of Australia, Canada, [[Chile]], Japan, the [[Republic of Korea]], New Zealand, and [[Portugal]], as well as several non-governmental organizations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.military.com/news/article/navy-news/usns-mercy-deploys-for-pacific.html?col=1186032311124 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606062100/http://www.military.com/news/article/navy-news/usns-mercy-deploys-for-pacific.html?col=1186032311124 |archivedate=2011-06-06 |title=USNS Mercy Deploys for Pacific |date=2 May 2008 |publisher=Navy News}}</ref> Originally intended to visit the [[Philippines]], Vietnam, the [[Federated States of Micronesia]], [[East Timor]], and [[Papua New Guinea]], USNS ''Mercy'' was to be redirected to the [[Bay of Bengal]] to provide immediate assistance to victims of the cyclone in [[Burma]], but relief efforts in Burma were called off. On 10 June, the humanitarian mission was temporarily suspended after one of its helicopters was shot at in the strife-torn southern Philippines area of [[Mindanao]]. Over the course of the deployment, ''Mercy'' would treat 91,000 patients, including performing 1,369 surgeries.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2010)===\n[[File:JS Kunisaki (LST-4003) and USNS Mercy (T-AH-19) in the South China Sea, -14 Jun. 2010 a.jpg|thumb|[[JDS Kunisaki (LST-4003)]], two Japanese [[Landing Craft Air Cushion]] hovercraft and USNS Mercy (T-AH-19) during Pacific Partnership 2010]]\n\nOn 24 February 2010, the Commander of the US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' will be the lead vessel of Pacific Partnership 2010, a continuation of the recurring humanitarian mission to Southeast Asia and Oceania.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=51550 |title=Pacific Fleet Announces Pacific Partnership 2010 |publisher=United States Navy |date=26 February 2010}}</ref> For Pacific Partnership 2010 ''Mercy'' visited Vietnam, Cambodia, Indonesia, and Timor Leste; treated 109,754 patients, and performed 1,580 surgeries.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2012)===\n3 May 2012 saw ''Mercy'' depart San Diego once again for Pacific Partnership 2012,<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/news/quarterdeck/msc-hospital-ship-departs-for-humanitarian-mission/article_7741b7fd-8cf1-59b5-9697-d69539e31ac4.html |title=MSC hospital ship departs for humanitarian mission |date=9 May 2012 |publisher=[[Military Sealift Command]]}}</ref> the latest deployment of the Pacific Partnership series. In an effort to further expand the scope of the mission of \"Preparing in Calm to Respond in Crisis\", many more man hours of Subject Matter Expert Exchange (SMEE) with host nations, Veterinary Care, and construction projects were performed compared to past ''Mercy'' deployments, building the capacity of host nations to respond to regional disasters in a coordinated manner. The ship visited Indonesia, Philippines, Vietnam, and Cambodia carrying personnel not only from the Department of Defense, but also 13 partner nations and 28 Non-Governmental Organizations.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=69582 |title=USNS Mercy returns following humanitarian mission in SE Asia|author1=Patrick, Meghan |date=14 September 2012 |publisher=United States Navy}}</ref>\n\nThe National Conflict Resolution Center honored the master and crew of hospital ship USNS Mercy with its 25th annual Peacemaker Award for its participation in Pacific Partnership (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.msc.navy.mil/sealift/2013/May/mercy.htm|title=USNS Mercy recognized for humanitarian work |publisher=Military Sealift Command|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Typhoon Haiyan (2013)===\nIn mid-November 2013, ''Mercy'' was ordered to activate for [[Operation Damayan]], the relief effort in response to the devastation caused by [[Typhoon Haiyan]], which struck the Philippines on 7 November 2013. However, ''Mercy'' was deactivated before sailing.<ref name=Navytimes20131113>{{cite news |url=https://news.usni.org/2013/11/14/navy-activates-hospital-ship-mercy-philippines-disaster-relief |title=Navy Activates Hospital Ship Mercy for Philippines Disaster Relief |work=USNI News |author1=LaGrone, Sam  |date=14 November 2013 |publisher=United States Naval Institute}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbs8.com/story/24077225/usns-mercy-deactivated-not-going-to-philippines |title=USNS Mercy deactivated, not going to Philippines |work=CBS8 San Diego |date=26 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Rim of the Pacific (RIMPAC) (2014)===\nThe US Navy announced that ''Mercy'' would be participating in RIMPAC 2014, a large multi-national naval exercise involving ships and personnel from 23 countries. In addition to providing real-world afloat acute medical and surgical care to personnel injured during the exercise, ''Mercy'' participated in multi-lateral Subject Matter Expert Exchanges with other military medical professionals. In addition, ''Mercy'' steamed with ''[[Peace Ark]]'', the hospital ship from the People's Republic of China during phases of the exercise.<ref>{{cite web|title=23 Nations to Participate in World's Largest Maritime Exercise|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=80804|publisher=United States Navy|date=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2015)===\nTen years after the relief effort for victims of the Indian Ocean tsunami, US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would once again participate in Pacific Partnership. Focusing on Subject Matter Expert Exchanges and Community Health Engagements, Pacific Partnership 15 looks to continue the mission of helping nations in the region \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". Countries hosting ''Mercy'' include Fiji, the Independent State of Papua New Guinea, Republic of the Philippines and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pacom.mil/Media/News/News-Article-View/Article/588664/10th-pacific-partnership-mission-prepares-to-renew-regional-ties/ |title=10th Pacific Partnership mission prepares to renew regional ties |publisher=United States Pacific Fleet|date=May 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2016)===\nCelebrating 10 years of Pacific Partnership, US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would continue to participate in the ongoing series of Disaster Preparedness missions. Focusing on local Subject Matter Expert Exchanges, Pacific Partnership 16 continues to \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". Countries that have invited ''Mercy'' include Timor Leste, Malaysia, Indonesia, Republic of the Philippines and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/194273/nations-come-together-finalize-plans-pacific-partnership-2016#.VylfjjArLuo|title=Nations Come Together, Finalize Plans for Pacific Partnership 2016|work=Commander, Western Logistics Group Pacific|publisher=US Department of Defense |date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2018)===\nUS Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would set sail to [[Sri Lanka]] for Pacific Partnership 2018 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PacificCommand/status/991885942888644609|title=U.S. Indo-Pacific Command on Twitter|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Seamen's Service]] at its annual Admiral of the Ocean Sea Awards (AOTOS) event honored the masters and crews of hospital ship USNS Mercy with Special Recognition Mariner's Plaque for its participation in Pacific Partnership (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mscsealift.dodlive.mil/2018/11/08/usns-mercy-recognized-for-pacific-partnership-mission/|title= USNS Mercy Recognized for Pacific Partnership Mission|publisher=Military Sealift Command|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Untitled operation in relationship with COVID-19 (2020) ===\n[[File:USNS Mercy Los Angeles, Ca.jpg|thumb|USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles, CA March 27, 2020]]\n''Mercy'' has been deployed to the West Coast of the US to provide hospital relief from the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] impact.<ref name=\"Covid\">{{cite news |last1=LaGrone |first1=Sam |title=Pentagon Preparing Navy Hospital Ships Mercy, Comfort for Coronavirus Response |url=https://news.usni.org/2020/03/17/pentagon-preparing-navy-hospital-ships-mercy-comfort-for-coronavirus-response |work=USNI News |publisher=United States Naval Institute |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The ship arrived and docked at the [[Port of Los Angeles]] cruise ship terminal on 27 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/27/usns-mercy-arrives-in-los-angeles-to-support-covid-19-response/ |title=USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles to support Covid-19 response|last=Correll|first=Diana Stancy|date=27 March 2020|work=Navy Times|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Her mission is to treat patients other than those with COVID-19, freeing up land-based hospitals to deal with the virus,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-covid-19-navy-hospital-ship-mercy-los-angeles-california/2336306/ |title=Help Arrives for Strained Hospitals When Navy Ship Mercy Docks at the Port of LA|last1=Lloyd|first1=Jonathan |last2=Chang|first2=Hetty |date=27 March 2020|work=NBC Los Angeles|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> similar to how {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20|6}} deployed [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_New_York_City|in New York]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Crowds Greet USNS Comfort in NYC Monday; Ship to Help Hospitals With Non-Coronavirus Patients |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/usns-comfort-arrives-in-nyc-monday-to-help-hospital-with-non-coronavirus-patients/2350317/ |website=NBC New York}}</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\n[[File:US Navy 100620-N-4044H-158 Cmdr. Matthew T. Provencher performs surgery on the right tibia of a Cambodian patient aboard Mercy.jpg|thumb|Orthopedic surgery performed in one of the ship's operating rooms.]]\n* Specifications:<ref>Norman Polmar, ''The Naval Institute Guide to the Ships and Aircraft of the U. S. Fleet'', Eighteenth Edition, Naval Institute Press, Annapolis, MD, 2005 ({{ISBN|1-59114-685-2}}), pp. 264-266.</ref>\n** Displacement:\n*** Full Load:  69,390 Tons\n*** Light:  24,275 Tons\n** Length:\n*** Overall:  894 Feet (272.6 Meters)\n*** Waterline:  854 5/6 Feet (260.6 Meters)\n** Beam:  105 3/4 Feet (32.25 Meters)\n** Draft:  32 5/6 Feet (10.0 Meters)\n** Propulsion:  1 Steam Turbine, 2 Boilers, 1 Shaft, 24,500 Shaft Horsepower\n** Speed:  17.5 Knots\n** Range:  13,400 Nautical Miles (24,817 Kilometers) at 17.5 Knots\n** Personnel:\n*** Merchant Marine:  16 ROS; 61 Active\n*** Navy Communications & Support:  58 (6 Officers, 52 Enlisted)\n*** Medical and Dental (Active Only):  1,156\n** Aviation:  Helicopter Landing Platform, 1 Spot\n** SPS-67 Surface Search\n* Patient Capacity:\n** Intensive care wards: 80 beds\n** Recovery wards: 20 beds\n** Intermediate care wards: 280 beds\n** Light care wards: 120 beds\n** Limited care wards: 500 beds\n** Total Patient Capacity: 1000 beds\n** Operating Rooms: 12\n* Departments and Facilities:\n** Casualty reception\n** Radiological services including CT\n** Main laboratory plus satellite lab\n** Central sterile processing\n** Medical supply/pharmacy\n** Physical therapy and burn care\n** Intensive Care Unit\n** Dental services\n** Optometry/lens lab\n** Morgue\n** Laundry\n** Burn Treatment\n** Angiography\n** Blood bank\n** Oxygen producing plants (two)\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n* [[Navy Unit Commendation]] - (Aug 1990-Mar 1991)\n* Navy [[Meritorious Unit Commendation]] - (Feb-Jul 1987, Sep 2001-Jun 2005, Apr-Sep 2006, May-Sep 2010)\n* [[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] - (Sep 1990-Mar 1991)\n* [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] - (Dec 2004-Feb 2005, [[Operation Unified Assistance]]; May-Jun 2006)\n* [[Philippine Republic Presidential Unit Citation]] - (Feb-Jul 1987)\n\n{|style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:auto; margin-left:auto; border: none;\" \n|colspan=\"3\"|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy_Unit_Commendation_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy_Meritorious_Unit_Commendation_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Southwest Asia Service Medal ribbon (1991-2016).svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|ribbon=Global_War_on_Terrorism_Expeditionary_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Humanitarian_Service_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|ribbon= Presidential Unit Citation (Philippines).svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|-\n!1st Row\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Navy Unit Commendation]]\n|-\n!2nd Row\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation]] w/3 [[service star]]s\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[National Defense Service Medal]] w/1 [[service star]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] w/3 [[campaign star]]s\n|-\n!3rd Row\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] w/1 [[service star]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Philippine Republic Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Operation Continuing Promise]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.mercy.navy.mil/ Official ''USNS Mercy (T-AH 19)'' Homepage]\n* {{NVR url|id=AH19|title=Naval Vessel Register entry for ''USNS Mercy''}}\n\n{{Mercy class hospital ship}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mercy (T-Ah-19)}}\n[[Category:Ships built in San Diego]]\n[[Category:1975 ships]]\n[[Category:Mercy-class hospital ships]]\n[[Category:Merchant ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tankers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hospitals and medical institutions associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other ships|USS Mercy}}\n{{short description|Hospital ship of the United States Navy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=yes}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:USNS Mercy leaving San Diego Bay.jpg|300px|USNS Mercy]]\n|Ship caption=USNS ''Mercy'' leaving San Diego Bay, May 2008\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag}}\n|Ship name=\n|Ship namesake=[[Mercy]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]]\n|Ship laid down= 12 June 1974 (As {{sclass-|San Clemente|oil tanker}} SS ''Worth'' MA-299)\n|Ship launched= 1 July 1975 (in [[San Diego, California]])\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=8 November 1986 (to US Navy)\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport= [[San Diego, California]]\n|Ship identification=*{{IMO Number|7390454}}\n* {{MMSI Number|367816000}}\n* [[Maritime call sign|Callsign]]: NMER\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=Active\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mercy|hospital ship}}\n|Ship capacity = 1000 patient beds\n|Ship displacement=65,552 tons<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship length={{cvt|894|ft}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship beam={{cvt|106|ft}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship propulsion=two boilers, two GE turbines, one shaft, {{cvt|24,500|hp|MW|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed={{cvt|17|kn}}<ref name=inv/>\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=*12 civilian and 58 military during [[Reduced Operating Status]]\n* 61 civilian and 1,214 military during Full Operating Status\n|Ship time to activate=5 days\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:USNS Mercy T-AH-19 2005.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' being refuelled at sea by {{USNS|Tippecanoe|T-AO 199|6}}, April 2005 during the ship's mission to aid victims of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]].]]\n[[File:USNS Mercy off Jolo.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' anchored off [[Jolo]], Philippines in June 2006.]]\n[[File:USNS Mercy off Dili.jpg|thumb|300px|''Mercy'' anchored in [[Dili]], East Timor, as part of \"Pacific Partnership 2008.\"]]\n[[File:US Navy 060704-N-1577S-002 Medical staff from Operation Smile and the Military Treatment Facility (MTF) aboard the Military Sealift Command (MSC) hospital ship USNS Mercy (T-AH 19), perform a cleft lip surgery.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Medical staff from [[Operation Smile]] and the [[Military Treatment Facility]] (MTF) aboard ''Mercy'', perform a [[cleft lip]] surgery during the ship's visit to provide humanitarian and civic assistance to the people of [[Bangladesh]].]]\n\n'''USNS ''Mercy'' (T-AH-19)''' is the [[lead ship]] of [[Mercy class hospital ship|her class]] of [[hospital ship]]s in non-commissioned service with the [[United States Navy]]. Her sister ship is {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20}}. She is the third US Navy ship to be named for the virtue [[mercy]]. In accordance with the [[Geneva Conventions]], ''Mercy'' and her crew do not carry any offensive weapons, though defensive weapons are available. Attacking ''Mercy'' is a [[war crime]].<ref>Diplomatic Conference of Geneva of 1949 {{cite web|url= http://www.icrc.org/ihl.nsf/COM/370-580040?OpenDocument|title=Chapter III: Hospital ships, Article 35 \u2013 Conditions not Depriving Hospital Ships of Protection|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Mercy'' was built as a {{sclass-|San Clemente|oil tanker}}, '''SS ''Worth''''', by [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]], San Diego, California, in 1976. Starting in July 1984, she was renamed and converted to a hospital ship by the same company. [[Ship naming and launching|Launched]] on 20 July 1985, ''Mercy'' was placed in service on 8 November 1986. She has a raised forecastle, a transom stern, a bulbous bow, an extended deckhouse with a forward bridge, and a helicopter-landing deck with a flight-control facility.\n\nThe conversions from oil tankers cost $208 million per ship and took 35 months to complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/tah-19-history.htm|title=T-AH 19 Mercy Class \u2013 Program History|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> The ''Mercy''-class hospital ships are the third largest ships in the US Navy Fleet by length, surpassed only by the nuclear-powered {{sclass-|Nimitz|aircraft carrier|5}}- and {{sclass-|Gerald R. Ford|aircraft carrier|0}} [[supercarrier]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |title=Patient Care |website=Command Facilities |publisher=USNS Mercy |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100323010700/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/Commandinfo/Pages/CommandFacilities.aspx |archivedate=23 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nHer primary mission is to provide rapid, flexible, and mobile acute medical and surgical services to support Marine Corps Air/Ground Task Forces deployed ashore, Army and Air Force units deployed ashore, and naval amphibious task forces and battle forces afloat. Secondarily, she provides mobile surgical hospital service for use by appropriate US Government agencies in disaster and humanitarian relief, and limited humanitarian care incident to these missions and to peacetime military operations.<ref name=\"med.navy.mil\">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |title=Command Mission |website=USNS Mercy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813132035/http://www.med.navy.mil/sites/usnsmercy/CommandInfo/Pages/mission.aspx |archivedate=2009-08-13|accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Mercy'', homeported in San Diego, is normally in reduced operating status. Her crew remains a part of the staff of [[Naval Medical Center San Diego]] until ordered to sea, at which time they have five days to fully activate the ship to a NATO Role III Medical Treatment Facility, the highest only to{{clarify|date=March 2020}} shore based fixed facilities outside the theater of operations.<ref name=\"med.navy.mil\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/logi-en/1997/lo-1610.htm |title=NATO Logistics Handbook: Chapter 16: Medical Support |work=nato.int |date=October 1997 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> Like most USNS ships, mariners from the US Navy's [[Military Sealift Command]] are responsible for navigation, propulsion, and most deck duties on board.<ref name=inv>{{cite web |url=https://www.militaryfactory.com/ships/detail.asp?ship_id=usns-mercy-t-ah-19-hospital-ship-usn |title=USNS Mercy (T-AH 19) Hospital Ship |work=Military Factory  |publisher=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> ''Mercy'' is as of 2012 part of MSC's Service Support Program. However, the \"Medical Treatment Facility\", or hospital on the ship, is commanded by a captain of the [[Medical Corps (United States Navy)|Navy Medical Corps]] or [[Navy Nurse Corps]].\n\nSince March 27, 2020, ''Mercy'' has been stationed in Los Angeles, California, to help combat the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-pandemic.html|title=Navy's 1,000-bed hospital ship arrives in Los Angeles to ease surge of coronavirus patients \u2013 here's what's inside|last=Macias|first=Amanda|date=2020-03-27|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Deployments==\n\n===Philippine Training Mission (1987)===\nOn 27 February 1987, ''Mercy'' began training while en route on a humanitarian cruise to the Philippines and the South Pacific. The staff included [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]], [[Indian Navy]], [[United States Army|U.S. Army]], and [[United States Air Force|U.S. Air Force]] active duty and reserve personnel; [[United States Public Health Service]]; medical providers from the [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]]; and [[Military Sealift Command|MSC]] civilian mariners. Over 62,000 outpatients and almost 1,000 inpatients were treated at seven Philippine and South Pacific ports. ''Mercy'' returned to [[Oakland, California]], on 13 July 1987.\n\n===Operation Desert Shield/Desert Storm (1990\u201391)===\nOn 9 August 1990, ''Mercy'' was activated in support of [[Gulf War#Operation Desert Shield|Operation Desert Shield]]. Departing on 15 August, she arrived in the [[Persian Gulf]] on 15 September. For the next six months, ''Mercy'' provided support to multinational allied forces. She admitted 690 patients and performed almost 300 surgeries. After treating the 21 American and two Italian repatriated [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]], she departed for home on 16 March 1991, arriving in Oakland on 23 April.\n\n===Operation Unified Assistance (2004)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego on 5 January 2005 en route to the [[2004 Indian Ocean tsunami|tsunami]]-devastated regions of [[South East Asia]], where she provided medical care to the victims of the disaster as part of [[Operation Unified Assistance]], and further care as part of Theater Security Cooperation Program 2005. Combined, she provided 108,000 patient services, rendered by members of the Department of Defense, Project Hope, and the [[U.S. Public Health Service|United States Public Health Service]].\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2006)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego in 2006 as the inaugural deployment of [[Pacific Partnership]], an ongoing Civic Assistance mission designed to \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". She visited several ports in the South Pacific Ocean including [[the Philippines]], Indonesia, and [[Banda Aceh]]. The ship's primary mission was to provide humanitarian assistance to these countries, and its staff included several non-governmental organizations, doctors from the armed services of several countries, as well as active-duty and reserve military providers from many branches of the US armed forces.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2008)===\nUSNS ''Mercy'' departed San Diego on 14 April 2008 for \"Pacific Partnership 2008\", a four-month humanitarian and civic [[Military deployment|deployment]] in Southeast Asia and Oceania. ''Mercy'', with its 900 officers and sailors, included 300 US health and construction experts. Partners participating in the mission included the nations of Australia, Canada, [[Chile]], Japan, the [[Republic of Korea]], New Zealand, and [[Portugal]], as well as several non-governmental organizations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.military.com/news/article/navy-news/usns-mercy-deploys-for-pacific.html?col=1186032311124 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606062100/http://www.military.com/news/article/navy-news/usns-mercy-deploys-for-pacific.html?col=1186032311124 |archivedate=2011-06-06 |title=USNS Mercy Deploys for Pacific |date=2 May 2008 |publisher=Navy News}}</ref> Originally intended to visit the [[Philippines]], Vietnam, the [[Federated States of Micronesia]], [[East Timor]], and [[Papua New Guinea]], USNS ''Mercy'' was to be redirected to the [[Bay of Bengal]] to provide immediate assistance to victims of the cyclone in [[Burma]], but relief efforts in Burma were called off. On 10 June, the humanitarian mission was temporarily suspended after one of its helicopters was shot at in the strife-torn southern Philippines area of [[Mindanao]]. Over the course of the deployment, ''Mercy'' would treat 91,000 patients, including performing 1,369 surgeries.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2010)===\n[[File:JS Kunisaki (LST-4003) and USNS Mercy (T-AH-19) in the South China Sea, -14 Jun. 2010 a.jpg|thumb|[[JDS Kunisaki (LST-4003)]], two Japanese [[Landing Craft Air Cushion]] hovercraft and USNS Mercy (T-AH-19) during Pacific Partnership 2010]]\n\nOn 24 February 2010, the Commander of the US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' will be the lead vessel of Pacific Partnership 2010, a continuation of the recurring humanitarian mission to Southeast Asia and Oceania.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=51550 |title=Pacific Fleet Announces Pacific Partnership 2010 |publisher=United States Navy |date=26 February 2010}}</ref> For Pacific Partnership 2010 ''Mercy'' visited Vietnam, Cambodia, Indonesia, and Timor Leste; treated 109,754 patients, and performed 1,580 surgeries.\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2012)===\n3 May 2012 saw ''Mercy'' depart San Diego once again for Pacific Partnership 2012,<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.militarynews.com/norfolk-navy-flagship/news/quarterdeck/msc-hospital-ship-departs-for-humanitarian-mission/article_7741b7fd-8cf1-59b5-9697-d69539e31ac4.html |title=MSC hospital ship departs for humanitarian mission |date=9 May 2012 |publisher=[[Military Sealift Command]]}}</ref> the latest deployment of the Pacific Partnership series. In an effort to further expand the scope of the mission of \"Preparing in Calm to Respond in Crisis\", many more man hours of Subject Matter Expert Exchange (SMEE) with host nations, Veterinary Care, and construction projects were performed compared to past ''Mercy'' deployments, building the capacity of host nations to respond to regional disasters in a coordinated manner. The ship visited Indonesia, Philippines, Vietnam, and Cambodia carrying personnel not only from the Department of Defense, but also 13 partner nations and 28 Non-Governmental Organizations.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=69582 |title=USNS Mercy returns following humanitarian mission in SE Asia|author1=Patrick, Meghan |date=14 September 2012 |publisher=United States Navy}}</ref>\n\nThe National Conflict Resolution Center honored the master and crew of hospital ship USNS Mercy with its 25th annual Peacemaker Award for its participation in Pacific Partnership (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.msc.navy.mil/sealift/2013/May/mercy.htm|title=USNS Mercy recognized for humanitarian work |publisher=Military Sealift Command|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Aftermath of Typhoon Haiyan (2013)===\nIn mid-November 2013, ''Mercy'' was ordered to activate for [[Operation Damayan]], the relief effort in response to the devastation caused by [[Typhoon Haiyan]], which struck the Philippines on 7 November 2013. However, ''Mercy'' was deactivated before sailing.<ref name=Navytimes20131113>{{cite news |url=https://news.usni.org/2013/11/14/navy-activates-hospital-ship-mercy-philippines-disaster-relief |title=Navy Activates Hospital Ship Mercy for Philippines Disaster Relief |work=USNI News |author1=LaGrone, Sam  |date=14 November 2013 |publisher=United States Naval Institute}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbs8.com/story/24077225/usns-mercy-deactivated-not-going-to-philippines |title=USNS Mercy deactivated, not going to Philippines |work=CBS8 San Diego |date=26 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Rim of the Pacific (RIMPAC) (2014)===\nThe US Navy announced that ''Mercy'' would be participating in RIMPAC 2014, a large multi-national naval exercise involving ships and personnel from 23 countries. In addition to providing real-world afloat acute medical and surgical care to personnel injured during the exercise, ''Mercy'' participated in multi-lateral Subject Matter Expert Exchanges with other military medical professionals. In addition, ''Mercy'' steamed with ''[[Peace Ark]]'', the hospital ship from the People's Republic of China during phases of the exercise.<ref>{{cite web|title=23 Nations to Participate in World's Largest Maritime Exercise|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=80804|publisher=United States Navy|date=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2015)===\nTen years after the relief effort for victims of the Indian Ocean tsunami, US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would once again participate in Pacific Partnership. Focusing on Subject Matter Expert Exchanges and Community Health Engagements, Pacific Partnership 15 looks to continue the mission of helping nations in the region \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". Countries hosting ''Mercy'' include Fiji, the Independent State of Papua New Guinea, Republic of the Philippines and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pacom.mil/Media/News/News-Article-View/Article/588664/10th-pacific-partnership-mission-prepares-to-renew-regional-ties/ |title=10th Pacific Partnership mission prepares to renew regional ties |publisher=United States Pacific Fleet|date=May 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2016)===\nCelebrating 10 years of Pacific Partnership, US Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would continue to participate in the ongoing series of Disaster Preparedness missions. Focusing on local Subject Matter Expert Exchanges, Pacific Partnership 16 continues to \"Prepare in Calm to Respond in Crisis\". Countries that have invited ''Mercy'' include Timor Leste, Malaysia, Indonesia, Republic of the Philippines and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/194273/nations-come-together-finalize-plans-pacific-partnership-2016#.VylfjjArLuo|title=Nations Come Together, Finalize Plans for Pacific Partnership 2016|work=Commander, Western Logistics Group Pacific|publisher=US Department of Defense |date=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Partnership (2018)===\nUS Pacific Fleet announced that ''Mercy'' would set sail to [[Sri Lanka]] for Pacific Partnership 2018 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/PacificCommand/status/991885942888644609|title=U.S. Indo-Pacific Command on Twitter|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United Seamen's Service]] at its annual Admiral of the Ocean Sea Awards (AOTOS) event honored the masters and crews of hospital ship USNS Mercy with Special Recognition Mariner's Plaque for its participation in Pacific Partnership (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mscsealift.dodlive.mil/2018/11/08/usns-mercy-recognized-for-pacific-partnership-mission/|title= USNS Mercy Recognized for Pacific Partnership Mission|publisher=Military Sealift Command|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Untitled operation in relationship with COVID-19 (2020) ===\n[[File:USNS Mercy Los Angeles, Ca.jpg|thumb|USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles, CA March 27, 2020]]\n''Mercy'' has been deployed to the West Coast of the US to provide hospital relief from the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] impact.<ref name=\"Covid\">{{cite news |last1=LaGrone |first1=Sam |title=Pentagon Preparing Navy Hospital Ships Mercy, Comfort for Coronavirus Response |url=https://news.usni.org/2020/03/17/pentagon-preparing-navy-hospital-ships-mercy-comfort-for-coronavirus-response |work=USNI News |publisher=United States Naval Institute |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The ship arrived and docked at the [[Port of Los Angeles]] cruise ship terminal on 27 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.navytimes.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/27/usns-mercy-arrives-in-los-angeles-to-support-covid-19-response/ |title=USNS Mercy arrives in Los Angeles to support Covid-19 response|last=Correll|first=Diana Stancy|date=27 March 2020|work=Navy Times|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Her mission is to treat patients other than those with COVID-19, freeing up land-based hospitals to deal with the virus,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-covid-19-navy-hospital-ship-mercy-los-angeles-california/2336306/ |title=Help Arrives for Strained Hospitals When Navy Ship Mercy Docks at the Port of LA|last1=Lloyd|first1=Jonathan |last2=Chang|first2=Hetty |date=27 March 2020|work=NBC Los Angeles|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> similar to how {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20|6}} deployed [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_New_York_City|in New York]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Crowds Greet USNS Comfort in NYC Monday; Ship to Help Hospitals With Non-Coronavirus Patients |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/usns-comfort-arrives-in-nyc-monday-to-help-hospital-with-non-coronavirus-patients/2350317/ |website=NBC New York}}</ref>\n\n==General characteristics==\n[[File:US Navy 100620-N-4044H-158 Cmdr. Matthew T. Provencher performs surgery on the right tibia of a Cambodian patient aboard Mercy.jpg|thumb|Orthopedic surgery performed in one of the ship's operating rooms.]]\n* Specifications:<ref>Norman Polmar, ''The Naval Institute Guide to the Ships and Aircraft of the U. S. Fleet'', Eighteenth Edition, Naval Institute Press, Annapolis, MD, 2005 ({{ISBN|1-59114-685-2}}), pp. 264-266.</ref>\n** Displacement:\n*** Full Load:  69,390 Tons\n*** Light:  24,275 Tons\n** Length:\n*** Overall:  894 Feet (272.6 Meters)\n*** Waterline:  854 5/6 Feet (260.6 Meters)\n** Beam:  105 3/4 Feet (32.25 Meters)\n** Draft:  32 5/6 Feet (10.0 Meters)\n** Propulsion:  1 Steam Turbine, 2 Boilers, 1 Shaft, 24,500 Shaft Horsepower\n** Speed:  17.5 Knots\n** Range:  13,400 Nautical Miles (24,817 Kilometers) at 17.5 Knots\n** Personnel:\n*** Merchant Marine:  16 ROS; 61 Active\n*** Navy Communications & Support:  58 (6 Officers, 52 Enlisted)\n*** Medical and Dental (Active Only):  1,156\n** Aviation:  Helicopter Landing Platform, 1 Spot\n** SPS-67 Surface Search\n* Patient Capacity:\n** Intensive care wards: 80 beds\n** Recovery wards: 20 beds\n** Intermediate care wards: 280 beds\n** Light care wards: 120 beds\n** Limited care wards: 500 beds\n** Total Patient Capacity: 1000 beds\n** Operating Rooms: 12\n* Departments and Facilities:\n** Casualty reception\n** Radiological services including CT\n** Main laboratory plus satellite lab\n** Central sterile processing\n** Medical supply/pharmacy\n** Physical therapy and burn care\n** Intensive Care Unit\n** Dental services\n** Optometry/lens lab\n** Morgue\n** Laundry\n** Burn Treatment\n** Angiography\n** Blood bank\n** Oxygen producing plants (two)\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n* [[Navy Unit Commendation]] - (Aug 1990-Mar 1991)\n* Navy [[Meritorious Unit Commendation]] - (Feb-Jul 1987, Sep 2001-Jun 2005, Apr-Sep 2006, May-Sep 2010)\n* [[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] - (Sep 1990-Mar 1991)\n* [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] - (Dec 2004-Feb 2005, [[Operation Unified Assistance]]; May-Jun 2006)\n\n{|style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:auto; margin-left:auto; border: none;\" \n|colspan=\"3\"|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy_Unit_Commendation_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Navy_Meritorious_Unit_Commendation_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=3|type=service-star|ribbon=Southwest Asia Service Medal ribbon (1991-2016).svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|ribbon=Global_War_on_Terrorism_Expeditionary_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Humanitarian_Service_ribbon.svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | {{ribbon devices|ribbon= Presidential Unit Citation (Philippines).svg{{!}}border|width=106}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|-\n!1st Row\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Navy Unit Commendation]]\n|-\n!2nd Row\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation]] w/3 [[service star]]s\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[National Defense Service Medal]] w/1 [[service star]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] w/3 [[campaign star]]s\n|-\n!3rd Row\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Humanitarian Service Medal]] w/1 [[service star]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Philippine Republic Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Operation Continuing Promise]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.mercy.navy.mil/ Official ''USNS Mercy (T-AH 19)'' Homepage]\n* {{NVR url|id=AH19|title=Naval Vessel Register entry for ''USNS Mercy''}}\n\n{{Mercy class hospital ship}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mercy (T-Ah-19)}}\n[[Category:Ships built in San Diego]]\n[[Category:1975 ships]]\n[[Category:Mercy-class hospital ships]]\n[[Category:Merchant ships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tankers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Ships involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Hospitals and medical institutions associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Shaggy151", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards and decorations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USNS_Mercy_(T-AH-19)"}
{"title_page": "Atlanta, Missouri", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Atlanta, Missouri\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Macon_County_Missouri_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Atlanta_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Atlanta, Missouri\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Missouri]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Missouri|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Macon County, Missouri|Macon]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_29.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 0.89\n|area_land_km2            = 0.89\n|area_water_km2           = 0.00\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 0.34\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 0.34\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.00\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 372\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 385\n|population_density_km2   = 422.86\n|population_density_sq_mi = 1096.49\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 275\n|elevation_ft             = 902\n|coordinates              = {{coord|39|53|57|N|92|28|49|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 63530\n|area_code                = [[Area code 660|660]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 29-02422<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0713468<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Atlanta''' is a city in [[Macon County, Missouri|Macon County]], [[Missouri]], United States. The population was 385 at the 2010 census.\n\nAtlanta residents are known for their love for their local \"Hornets\" sports teams and the local school colors of blue and white.\n\n==History==\nAtlanta was [[plat]]ted in 1858.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://shsmo.org/manuscripts/ramsay/ramsay_macon.html  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624070636/http://shsmo.org/manuscripts/ramsay/ramsay_macon.html | archivedate = June 24, 2016 | url-status = live | title=Macon County Place Names, 1928\u20131945 | publisher=The State Historical Society of Missouri| accessdate= October 30, 2016}}</ref> The community was named after [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_RfAuAAAAYAAJ | title=How Missouri Counties, Towns and Streams Were Named | publisher=The State Historical Society of Missouri | author=Eaton, David Wolfe | year=1916 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_RfAuAAAAYAAJ/page/n88 191]}}</ref> A post office called Atlanta has been in operation since 1868.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.postalhistory.com/postoffices.asp?task=display&state=MO&county=Macon | title=Post Offices| publisher=Jim Forte Postal History | accessdate=30 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 1935 a [[Trans World Airlines|TWA]] [[DC-2]] en route from [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], to [[Washington, D.C.]] became lost in heavy fog near Atlanta. Running out of fuel, the pilot attempted an emergency landing but crashed, which killed four and injured several others. Among the dead was United States Senator [[Bronson Cutting]] (R-[[New Mexico]]). The crash made national headlines and prompted Congress to commission the [[Copeland Committee]] report on air traffic safety.<ref>{{cite web  | title = Transport: Ceiling Zero  | publisher = Time Magazine  | date = May 13, 1935  | url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,754759,00.html  | accessdate = September 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAtlanta is located at {{coord|39|53|57|N|92|28|49|W|type:city}} (39.899177, -92.480161).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|0.34|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, all land.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-01-25 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 523\n|1920= 536\n|1930= 497\n|1940= 507\n|1950= 438\n|1960= 386\n|1970= 377\n|1980= 441\n|1990= 411\n|2000= 450\n|2010= 385\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=372\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-07-08}}</ref> of 2010, there were 385 people, 157 households, and 104 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1132.4|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 189 housing units at an average density of {{convert|555.9|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 97.1% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.3% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.5% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 2.1% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.3% of the population.\n\nThere were 157 households of which 38.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 14.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 6.4% had a male householder with no wife present, and 33.8% were non-families. 30.6% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 2.99.\n\nThe median age in the city was 37.9 years. 28.1% of residents were under the age of 18; 5.1% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 28.6% were from 25 to 44; 22.1% were from 45 to 64; and 16.1% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 47.3% male and 52.7% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 450 people, 173 households, and 129 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,314.2 people per square mile (511.0/km\u00b2). There were 199 housing units at an average density of 581.2/sq&nbsp;mi (226.0/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 99.11% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.22% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], and 0.67% from two or more races.\n\nThere were 173 households out of which 39.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 56.1% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 15.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.4% were non-families. 23.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.60 and the average family size was 3.03.\n\nIn the city the population was spread out with 30.7% under the age of 18, 7.8% from 18 to 24, 30.7% from 25 to 44, 18.9% from 45 to 64, and 12.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 31 years. For every 100 females there were 90.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 84.6 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $33,571, and the median income for a family was $39,271. Males had a median income of $25,673 versus $16,875 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $14,940. About 7.3% of families and 9.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.5% of those under age 18 and 11.5% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Churches==\nThe Atlanta community is home to several churches including: The [http://www.sbc.net/redirect.asp?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eatlantafbc%2Ecom Atlanta First Baptist Church], [http://www.facebook.com/home.php#/pages/Atlanta-MO/Atlanta-Christian-Church/113464846992?ref=ts Atlanta Christian Church], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727094656/http://www.moumethodist.org/church_detail.asp?TableName=oChurches&PKValue=727 Atlanta United Methodist Church], and [http://www.atlantachurch.blogspot.com Church WithOut Walls, a non-denominational ministry based in the community]. Three rural churches are also a part of the Atlanta community: [https://web.archive.org/web/20110727094446/http://www.moumethodist.org/church_detail.asp?TableName=oChurches&PKValue=790 Mt. Zion East United Methodist Church], and Southern Baptist congregations at [http://www.sbc.net/churchsearch/church.asp?ID=0000%2D63530 Chariton Ridge] and [http://www.sbc.net/churchsearch/church.asp?ID=4235%2D63530 Mt. Tabor.]\n\n==Annual events==\nThe community hosts the [http://www.goatlantahomecoming.com \"Atlanta Homecoming\"] every last full weekend in June in the town center, Atterberry Park.\n\nOther downtown activities include the annual \"Big Wheels\" event hosted by the [https://www.facebook.com/Atlanta-C-3-PTO-729268693819468/ Atlanta PTO] every September and an Egg Hunt hosted by Crossroads Christian Church of Macon, MO the Saturday before Easter every year.\n\nSports activities at the school include a Little Dribblers Tournament hosted by the PTO in March and the Pee Wee Baseball Tournament held in May.\n\n==Education==\nThe [http://www.atlanta.k12.mo.us/ local school district], Atlanta C-3 school district averages about 200 students, K-12, annually. In 2007, the district was recognized as a National Blue Ribbon School by the United States Department of Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalblueribbonschools.ed.gov/awardwinners/winning/17mo107pu_atlanta_elementary_school.html|title=NBRS Atlanta Elementary School of Atlanta, MO|website=National Blue Ribbon Schools Program|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Atlanta Elementary was ranked 7th out of 1,039 elementary schools in Missouri, based on Missouri's Assessment Program test scores.\n\nThe [https://www.facebook.com/gohomepioneer Home Pioneer 4-H Club] is based in Atlanta and currently has 83 members, making it one of the largest 4-H clubs in Missouri.\n\n==Recreation==\nVisitors to the area include hunters seeking whitetail deer and turkey.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{alumni|residents|date=May 2019}}\n* [[AT Still|Andrew Taylor Still]], considered the founder of osteopathic medicine, lived in the Atlanta area (rural Barnesville) as a young adult and local teacher. Barnesville is in the Atlanta zip code and school district.\n* [[Milton A. Romjue|Milton Romjue]], Democrat, served in the United States Congress from 1917-1921 and again from 1923\u20131943. He attended local schools and lived east of the Love Lake area, now in the Atlanta zip code and school district. Romjue was a postal service reformer and supporter of President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s [[New Deal]] legislation - especially [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], help for farmers, and wounded military veterans. The congressman also worked closely with other Missouri politicians to secure for the state military bases such as [[Fort Leonard Wood]] and [[Camp Crowder]] as America geared up for [[World War II]]. Romjue also served as a county judge.\n* [[Wat Arnold|Samuel W. \"Wat\" Arnold]], Republican, served in the United States Congress from 1943\u20131949. Arnold served as a superintendent at Atlanta schools and later returned to the area in 1905 to start a fifty-plus year career as a lumberman. He later moved \"Arnold Lumber Company\" to [[Kirksville, Missouri|Kirksville]], seeking a larger customer base. He defeated Atlanta area native Romjue in the general election of 1942.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://dl.mospace.umsystem.edu/mu/islandora/object/mu%3A138699 Historic Sanborn Map of Atlanta (1918)] from [[University of Missouri System|University of Missouri]] Digital Library\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Macon County, Missouri}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Cities in Macon County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:1858 establishments in Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Atlanta, Missouri\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Macon_County_Missouri_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Atlanta_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Atlanta, Missouri\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Missouri]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Missouri|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Macon County, Missouri|Macon]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date       